        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Jacob Voorsanger.<lb/>
                Box 191.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; March 23&#91;&#44;&#93; 1885<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev S Morais<lb/>
                Rev and dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In cases of emergency I know I may always<lb/> appeal to you. You wrote me already two years ago that I should be stationed near<lb/> the center of Jewish population. An opportunity presents itself first&#91;&#63;&#93; at present&#44; <lb/>but I need all the assistance I can get. Some weeks ago a letter from Dr Kohler<lb/> led me to believe that my application for the position of assistant minister<lb/> in Temple Emanuel would be duly considered. It fairly took my breath away<lb/> but upon second sober thought I saw no reason why I should not strike boldly<lb/> for a main chance. I applied to the President&#44; and wrote at the same time to Dr.<lb/> Gottheil&#44; advising him of my application. I was much disturbed about the issue<lb/> for I had some reason to believe that Dr. Gottheil did not think kindly of me. To<lb/> my great surprise the Doctor&#39;s answer was kind&#44; cordial and encouraging<lb/> in the highest degree&#59; he informed me that Mr May&#91;&#63;&#93; was favorably impressed<lb/> with my application and advised me to send my papers and <hi rend="underline">curriculum</hi><lb/> vitae at once. I have done so&#59; and now it remains for me to emphasise my<lb/>  statements with such pressure as I can command. It is a great under&#45;<lb/>taking&#44; but &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; if I succeed I think I can do justice to the position.<lb/> I have not been idle during the long years&#44; and have followed  up<lb/> my college studies autodidactically. You may wonder&#44; that I seek<lb/> your assistance in this matter. It is just because you are a conservative<lb/> minister&#44; whose integrity is above suspicion&#44; that I believe you can do<lb/> &#94; me more service than the slip shod rabbis of the west. Your name is a<lb/> power with the New York Ministers&#44; reform or conservative. I make<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>bold to ask you to write to Dr. Gottheil or to Mr May&#91;&#63;&#93; concerning your<lb/> knowledge of me&#44; and I am confident that your statements will have<lb/> more value than any other reference I can give. The fact is you know<lb/> me fully as well as anyone in this country&#44; and it is for that<lb/> reason I ask you. Certainly&#44; if you scruple to volunteer any infor&#45;<lb/>mation I will be satisfied&#59; but I beg you to consider the matter&#44;<lb/> as I stand on the eve of a new life and may with proper as&#45;<lb/>sistance be called to a field in which I can use my ener&#45;<lb/>gy to the best advantage&#44; Pardon the boldness of the re&#45;<lb/>quest&#44; if you cannot grant it&#44; and believe me always<lb/></p>
            <p>Faithfully yours<lb/>
                Jacob Voorsanger<lb/></p>
        </body>
